answer:
We are looking for a number that leaves a remainder of $3$ when divided by $7$ and a remainder of $1$ when divided by $5$. We can write this as a system of congruences: \begin{align*}
n&\equiv 3\pmod{7}\\
n&\equiv 1\pmod{5}
\end{align*} The first congruence tells us that $n=7a+3$ for some integer $a$. Substituting this into the second congruence, we get $7a+3\equiv 1\pmod{5}$, or $2a\equiv -2\pmod{5}$. Since $-2\equiv 3\pmod{5}$, we have $2a\equiv 3\pmod{5}$. Multiplying both sides by the modular inverse of $2$ modulo $5$, which is $3$, we get $a\equiv 4\pmod{5}$. Therefore, $a=5b+4$ for some integer $b$, and $n=7(5b+4)+3=35b+31$. Since $n<40$, we have $35b+31<40$, so $b=0$. Therefore, $n=\boxed{31}$.

