answer:
The quadratic equation $2x^2 + 5x + b = 0$ has rational roots if and only if its discriminant is a perfect square. The discriminant of the quadratic is $5^2 - 4(2)(b) = 25 - 8b$. We need $25 - 8b$ to be a perfect square. Since $b$ is a positive integer, $25 - 8b$ is a perfect square less than 25. The only perfect squares less than 25 are $0, 1, 4, 9, 16$. We can solve for $b$ in each case: \begin{align*}
25 - 8b &= 0 \\
25 &= 8b \\
b &= \frac{25}{8}
\end{align*} which is not an integer. \begin{align*}
25 - 8b &= 1 \\
24 &= 8b \\
b &= 3
\end{align*} which is an integer. \begin{align*}
25 - 8b &= 4 \\
21 &= 8b \\
b &= \frac{21}{8}
\end{align*} which is not an integer. \begin{align*}
25 - 8b &= 9 \\
16 &= 8b \\
b &= 2
\end{align*} which is an integer. \begin{align*}
25 - 8b &= 16 \\
9 &= 8b \\
b &= \frac{9}{8}
\end{align*} which is not an integer. Therefore, the only possible positive integer values of $b$ are $b = 2$ and $b = 3$, and their sum is $2 + 3 = \boxed{5}$.

