Then
\[\cos \alpha = \cos \left( \beta + \frac{\pi}{3} \right) = \cos \beta \cos \frac{\pi}{3} - \sin \beta \sin \frac{\pi}{3} = \frac{1}{2} \cos \beta - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin \beta.\]Since $\cos \alpha = 2 \cos \beta,$
\[2 \cos \beta = \frac{1}{2} \cos \beta - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin \beta.\]Then
\[\frac{3}{2} \cos \beta = - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin \beta,\]so $\tan \beta = -\sqrt{3}.$  Hence, $\beta = \frac{2 \pi}{3} + k \pi$ for some integer $k.$

If $k$ is even, then $\beta$ is in the second quadrant, so $\cos \beta$ is negative.  If $k$ is odd, then $\beta$ is in the fourth quadrant, so $\cos \beta$ is positive.  But $\cos \beta = x,$ which must be in the interval $[-1, 1].$  Therefore, the only possible value of $\beta$ is $\frac{2 \pi}{3},$ which gives us $x = \boxed{-\frac{1}{2}}.$

