We can use a Venn diagram to solve this problem.  [asy]
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
draw(Circle((0,0), 2));
draw(Circle((2,0), 2));
draw((0,0)--(2,0), EndArrow);
draw((2,0)--(4,0), EndArrow);
label("85", (1,2), N);
label("27", (2,0), N);
label("48", (3,-2), N);
label("46", (2,-4), N);
[/asy] We see that the number of employees that can monitor water pollution is the sum of the number of employees that can monitor only water pollution and the number of employees that can monitor both.  So, the number of employees that can monitor only water pollution is $85-27=58$.  Similarly, the number of employees that can monitor only air pollution is $73-27=46$.  So, the minimum number of employees that need to be hired is $58+27+46=\boxed{131}$.

ref_solution:
There are $85+73=158$ jobs to be done.  $27$ people do two of the jobs, so that leaves $158 - 27\cdot 2 = 158-54 = 104$ jobs remaining.  The remaining workers do one job each, so we need $27 + 104 = \boxed{131}$ workers.

We also might construct the Venn Diagram below.  We start in the middle of the diagram, with the 27 workers who do both:

[asy]
