Let $a = \sin^{-1} \frac{3}{5}$ and $b = \tan^{-1} 2.$  Then $\sin a = \frac{3}{5}$ and $\tan b = 2.$  We want to compute $\sin (a + b).$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (0,3/5);
B = (4/5,3/5);
C = (4/5,0);
O = (0,0);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(O--A);
draw(O--B);
draw(O--C);

label("$a$", A, NW);
label("$b$", B, NE);
label("$c$", C, S);
label("$d$", O, W);
[/asy]

From the right triangle shown, we see that $\cos a = \frac{4}{5}.$  Also, $\cos b = \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}$ and $\sin b = \frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\sin (a + b) &= \sin a \cos b + \cos a \sin b \\
&= \frac{3}{5} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}} + \frac{4}{5} \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{5}} \\
&= \frac{11}{5 \sqrt{5}} \\
&= \boxed{\frac{11 \sqrt{5}}{25}}.
\end{align*}

